<p><b>Alcohol by volume</b> (abbreviated as <b>alc/vol</b> or <b>ABV</b>) i=
s a common measure of the amount of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Alcohol_(drug)" title=3D"Alcohol (drug)">alcohol</a> contained in a given=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcoholic_beverage" title=3D"Alco=
holic beverage">alcoholic beverage</a>. It is defined as the volume the eth=
anol in the liquid would take if separated from the rest of the solution, d=
ivided by the volume of the solution, both at 20&nbsp;=C2=B0C (68&nbsp;=C2=
=B0F).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by_volume#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by=
_volume#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by_volume#cite_note-3"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by_volume#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Pure ethanol is li=
ghter than water, with a density of 0.78945&nbsp;g/mL (0.82353&nbsp;oz/US&n=
bsp;fl&nbsp;oz; 0.79122&nbsp;oz/imp&nbsp;fl&nbsp;oz; 0.45633&nbsp;oz/cu&nbs=
p;in). The <b>alc/vol</b> standard is used worldwide. The <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Organization_of_Legal_Metrology" titl=
e=3D"International Organization of Legal Metrology">International Organizat=
ion of Legal Metrology</a> has <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eth=
anol_(data_page)#Properties_of_aqueous_ethanol_solutions" title=3D"Ethanol =
(data page)">tables of density of water=E2=80=93ethanol mixtures</a> at dif=
ferent concentrations and temperatures.
</p><p>In some countries, e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fra=
nce" title=3D"France">France</a>, alcohol by volume is often referred to as=
 <b>degrees Gay-Lussac</b> (after the French chemist <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Louis_Gay-Lussac" title=3D"Joseph Louis Gay-Lussa=
c">Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac</a>),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by_volume#cite_note-5"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> although there is a slight difference since the Gay-Lussac conventi=
on uses the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Standard=
_Atmosphere" title=3D"International Standard Atmosphere">International Stan=
dard Atmosphere</a> value for temperature, 15&nbsp;=C2=B0C (59&nbsp;=C2=B0F=
).
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Volume_change">Volume chang=
e</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAlcohol_by=
_volume&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Volume ch=
ange"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Excess_Volume_Mixture_of_Ethanol_and_Water.pn=
g" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/w=
ikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/Excess_Volume_Mixture_of_Ethanol_and_Water.png/=
443px-Excess_Volume_Mixture_of_Ethanol_and_Water.png" decoding=3D"async" wi=
dth=3D"370" height=3D"322" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"443=
" data-file-height=3D"386"></a><figcaption>Change in volume with increasing=
 alc/vol.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Mixing two solutions of alcohol of different strengths usually causes a =
change in volume. Mixing pure water with a solution less than 24% by mass c=
auses a slight increase in total volume, whereas the mixing of two solution=
s above 24% causes a decrease in volume.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by_volume#cite_not=
e-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> The phenomenon of volume changes due to mixing dissimilar s=
olutions is called "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_molar_=
volume" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Partial molar volume">partial molar =
volume</a>". Water and ethanol are both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Chemical_polarity" title=3D"Chemical polarity">polar</a> solvents. Wh=
en water is added to ethanol, the smaller water molecules are attracted to =
the ethanol's hydroxyl group, and each molecule alters the polarity field o=
f the other. The attraction allows closer spacing between molecules than is=
 usually found in non-polar mixtures.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template =
Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation neede=
d"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October=
 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>Thus, alc/vol is not the same as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Volume_fraction" title=3D"Volume fraction">volume fraction</a> expres=
sed as a percentage. Volume fraction, which is widely used in chemistry (co=
mmonly denoted as v/v), is defined as the volume of a particular component =
divided by the sum of all components in the mixture when they are measured =
separately. For example, to make 100&nbsp;mL of 50% alc/vol ethanol solutio=
n, water would be added to 50 mL of ethanol to make up exactly 100 mL. Wher=
eas to make a 50% v/v ethanol solution, 50&nbsp;mL of ethanol and 50&nbsp;m=
L of water could be mixed but the resulting volume of solution will measure=
 less than 100&nbsp;mL due to the change of volume on mixing, and will cont=
ain a higher concentration of ethanol.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by_volume#cite_note-=
7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> The difference is not large, with the maximum difference bein=
g less than 2.5%, and less than 0.5% difference for concentrations under 20=
%.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space=
:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_n=
eeded" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs =
references to reliable sources. (October 2024)">citation needed</span></a><=
/i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Threshold_levels">Threshold=
 levels</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAlco=
hol_by_volume&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Thr=
eshold levels"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Legal_thresholds">Legal thr=
esholds</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAlco=
hol_by_volume&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Leg=
al thresholds"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>Some drinks have requirements of alcoholic content in order to be certif=
ied as a certain alcohol brand or label. For example, in the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom" title=3D"United Kingdom">United =
Kingdom</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States" ti=
tle=3D"United States">United States</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Canada" title=3D"Canada">Canada</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/European_Union" title=3D"European Union">European Union</a> <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whisky" title=3D"Whisky">whisky</a> =
is legally required to be no less than 40% ABV bottled.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by_=
volume#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Low-alcohol beers (&lt;0.5) are considered in some countries such as=
 Iran as permitted (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halal" title=
=3D"Halal">halal</a>) despite alcohol being banned.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by_volu=
me#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> However, the level of alcohol-free beers is typi=
cally the lowest commercially sold 0.05.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Templa=
te Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation ne=
eded"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (Octo=
ber 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Biological_thresholds">Biol=
ogical thresholds</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DAlcohol_by_volume&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Biological thresholds"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>It is near impossible for a healthy person to become intoxicated drinkin=
g low-alcohol drinks. The low concentration severely limits the rate of int=
ake, which is easily dispatched by human metabolism. Quickly drinking 1.5&n=
bsp;L of 0.4% alc/vol beer in an hour resulted in a maximum of 0.0056% <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content" title=3D"Blood =
alcohol content">BAC</a> in a study of German volunteers.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_=
by_volume#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Healthy human kidneys can only excrete=
 0.8=E2=80=931.0&nbsp;L of water per hour, making <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Water_intoxication" title=3D"Water intoxication">water into=
xication</a> likely to set in before any alcoholic intoxication.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-sa_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Alcohol_by_volume#cite_note-sa-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The process of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethanol_ferm=
entation" title=3D"Ethanol fermentation">ethanol fermentation</a> will slow=
 down and eventually come to a halt as the alcohol produced becomes too con=
centrated for the yeast to tolerate, defining an upper limit of alc/vol for=
 non-distilled alcoholic drinks. The typical tolerance for beer yeasts is a=
t 8=E2=80=9312%, while wine yeasts typically range from 14=E2=80=9318%, wit=
h speciality ones reaching 20% alc/vol. Any higher would require distillati=
on, producing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liquor" title=3D"Liq=
uor">liquor</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by_volume#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Alcohol_by_volume#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
