<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Other_methods_of_specifying=
_alcohol_content">Other methods of specifying alcohol content</h2><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAlcohol_by_volume&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Other methods of specif=
ying alcohol content"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Alcohol_proof">Alcohol proo=
f</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAlcohol_by=
_volume&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Alcohol =
proof"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_proof" title=
=3D"Alcohol proof">Alcohol proof</a></div>
<p>Another way of specifying the amount of alcohol content is alcohol <i>pr=
oof</i>, which in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_State=
s" title=3D"United States">United States</a> is twice the alcohol-by-volume=
 (alc/vol) number. This may lead to confusion over similar products bought =
in varying regions that have different names on country-specific labels. Fo=
r example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stroh" title=3D"Stroh">=
Stroh</a> rum that is 80% ABV is advertised and labeled as <i>Stroh 80</i> =
when sold in Europe, but is named <i>Stroh 160</i> when sold in the United =
States.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-=
space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citat=
ion_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim n=
eeds references to reliable sources. (October 2024)">citation needed</span>=
</a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom" titl=
e=3D"United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>, proof is 1.75 times the number (ex=
pressed as a percentage).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERegan2003_25-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by_volume#c=
ite_note-FOOTNOTERegan2003-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBerry=
1998_22-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alc=
ohol_by_volume#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBerry1998-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, 40%=
 alc/vol is 80 proof in the US and 70 proof in the UK. However, since 1980,=
 alcohol proof in the UK has been replaced by alc/vol as a measure of alcoh=
ol content, avoiding confusion between the UK and US proof standards.<sup c=
lass=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;=
">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" t=
itle=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs referenc=
es to reliable sources. (October 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</su=
p>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Alcohol_by_weight">Alcohol =
by weight</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAl=
cohol_by_volume&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: =
Alcohol by weight"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the United States, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arkansas"=
 title=3D"Arkansas">Arkansas</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Kansas" title=3D"Kansas">Kansas</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Mississippi" title=3D"Mississippi">Mississippi</a>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Carolina" title=3D"South Carolina">South Carolin=
a</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tennessee" title=3D"Ten=
nessee">Tennessee</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_by_volume#cite_note-26"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 regulate and tax alcoholic beverages according to <b>alcohol by weight</b>=
 (<b>ABW</b>), expressed as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conc=
entration#Mass_percentage_.28fraction.29" title=3D"Concentration">percentag=
e of total mass</a>. The alc/vol value of a beverage is always higher than =
the ABW.
</p><p>Because ABW measures the proportion of the drink's mass which is alc=
ohol, while alc/vol is the proportion of the drink's volume which is alcoho=
l, the two values are in the same proportion as the drink's density is with=
 the density of alcohol. Therefore, one can use the following equation to c=
onvert between ABV and ABW:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle {\text{ABV}}=3D{\text{ABW}}\times {\frac {\text{density=
 of beverage}}{\text{density of alcohol}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>ABV</mtext>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>ABW</mtext>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=C3=97<!-- =C3=97 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mtext>density of beverage</mtext>
            <mtext>density of alcohol</mtext>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\text{ABV}}=
=3D{\text{ABW}}\times {\frac {\text{density of beverage}}{\text{density of =
alcohol}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/3c34adcf19ea4bc237eaa975822b8efe88460121" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.338ex; width:36.886ex; height:5.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {=
\text{ABV}}=3D{\text{ABW}}\times {\frac {\text{density of beverage}}{\text{=
density of alcohol}}}}"></span>
</p><p>At relatively low alc/vol, the alcohol percentage by weight is about=
 4/5 of the alc/vol (e.g., 3.2% ABW is about 4% alc/vol).<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_=
by_volume#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, because of the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miscibility" title=3D"Miscibility">miscibility</=
a> of alcohol and water, the conversion factor is not constant but rather d=
epends upon the concentration of alcohol.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Templ=
ate Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation n=
eeded"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (Oct=
ober 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
